Lesson 7 - Sentiment Analysis¶

This assignment requires that you build a sentiment analysis classifier for a series of tweets. The data consists of a file "twitter_data.csv". The file contains 16,000 tweets with their respective score. The attributes are the sentences, and the score is either 4 (for positive) or 0 (for negative).

Question 1: Generate word cloud for positive sentiment.

In [ ]:
def preprocess(text, list_of_steps):
    for step in list_of_steps:
        if step == "remove_non_ascii":
            text = "".join([x for x in text if ord(x) < 128])
        elif step == "lowercase":
            text = text.lower()
        elif step == "remove_punctuation":
            punct_exclude = set(string.punctuation)
            text = "".join(char for char in text if char not in punct_exclude)
        elif step == "remove_numbers":
            # MH: probably could just use some filter, but let's use an approach similar to the previous steps
            digits = set("0123456789".split())
            text = "".join(char for char in text if char not in digits)
        elif step == "remove_stopwords":
            stops = STOPWORDS
            word_list = text.split(" ")
            text_words = [word for word in word_list if word not in stops]
            text = " ".join(text_words)
        elif step == "stem_words":
            lmtzr = WordNetLemmatizer()
            stemmed_words = [lmtzr.lemmatize(word) for word in text.split(" ")]
            text = " ".join(stemmed_words)
        elif step == "strip_whitespace":
            text = " ".join(text.split())
    return text


steps = [
    "remove_non_ascii",
    "lowercase",
    "remove_punctuation",
    "remove_numbers",
    "strip_whitespace",
    "remove_stopwords",
    "stem_words",
]

df["clean_tweet"] = df["tweet_text"].apply(lambda s: preprocess(s, steps))
pos_clean_string = ",".join(df.loc[df["sentiment_label"] == 4, :]["clean_tweet"])
wordcloud = WordCloud(
    max_words=50, width=2500, height=1500, background_color="black", stopwords=STOPWORDS
).generate(pos_clean_string)

Question 3: Split data where test size = 40000, random_state = 42. Max_df=0.5, max_features = 6228,

In [ ]:
# Declare the TFIDF vectorizer.
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(
    sublinear_tf=True, stop_words=list(STOPWORDS), max_df=0.5, max_features=6228
)

# Fit the vectorizer over the dataset
clean_texts = df["clean_tweet"]
tf_idf_tweets = vectorizer.fit_transform(clean_texts)

# split the data
y_targets = np.array(df["sentiment_label"])
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    tf_idf_tweets, y_targets, random_state=42, test_size=40000
)

model = SGDClassifier(
    loss="modified_huber",
    learning_rate="adaptive",
    penalty="elasticnet",
    alpha=10**-7, # this is the default, effectively,
    eta0=0.001
)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

Question 6: What conclusions can you draw from the model?

The model achieves convergence pretty quickly, even with lower alpha coefficient of learning rate and eta0 coefficient for adaptive learning rate. With this values the model shows the score of 0.76, which good, with some space for improvement. The model does a pretty good job of predicting the sentiment of the tweets.

[Bonus] Question 7: If you are to build a sentiment analysis model, would it be dependent on the source of data?

The source of the data will definitely determine what preprocessing will be applied. Tweets (especially before introducing longer than 160 characters) are limited in terms of the length, so their processing can be handled with less resources. The more complex data sources (books, essays, articles) will require more complex preprocessing.

As for the model itself, the data source will also determine the size of of the TF-IDF vectors.
